Defines the `ctx-summarize` binary's argv surface (via `clap`) and wires parsed args into `runner::run`, writing the resulting summary as pretty JSON to a caller-supplied writer.

Only one subcommand exists today: `Paths { paths: Vec<String> }`, taking an explicit list of repo-relative source paths — there's no "diff mode" or glob expansion here. `--prompts` (default `"prompts"`) and `--approve` are global flags available on any subcommand. `--approve` bypasses `runner::scope_check`'s guard against accidentally summarizing too many files (`MAX_TARGETS`, enforced in runner.rs) — omitting it on a large explicit path list causes `dispatch` to return an error before doing any work.

`dispatch<F: Fs, A: Agent, W: Write>(fs: &F, agent: &A, cli: &Cli, out: &mut W) -> Result<(), SummError>` is the sole entry point; it's generic over the `Fs`/`Agent` traits so tests can inject fakes, and always uses `NoProgress` (no progress reporting from the CLI path — callers wanting progress must use `runner::run` directly). JSON serialization/write failures are wrapped as `SummError::Io` with `path: "<stdout>"`, distinguishing them from real filesystem I/O errors elsewhere in `SummError`'s variants.